[2]
Date: 7 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New India Press 8 Jun 2003 0:00 IST [edited]
<http://www.newindpress.com/Newsitems.asp?ID=IEH20030607114740&Title=Top+Stories&rLink=0?>

West Bengal doctors fight mystery disease
-----------------
Panic-stricken parents on Saturday crowded makeshift health centres
in a central West Bengal district where a mysterious disease has
reportedly killed 32 children over 10 days. A team of doctors sent
from here to the Lalgola block of Murshidabad district, some 200 km
to the north, treated scores of children in makeshift camps that have
been swamped by anxious parents clutching their ailing babies.
An unknown disease spreading though 5 villages in Lalgola has
reportedly killed at least 32 children, but West Bengal's health
services director Prabhakar Chatterjee has put the toll at 19.
Health officials working in the affected areas say they cannot
pinpoint the exact death toll, because many deaths in remote places
could be going unreported. Death figures from independent sources in
Kulgachi, Kadamtala, Kurchidanga, Natundiyar, and Jagarpara villages,
where the disease has been reported, totalled 32. All the victims
were under 5 years [old].
About 250 children, many of who were being treated in the makeshift
medical centres, were showing symptoms of the strange disease like
high fever, salivation, and convulsions. Doctors, who suspect the
case to be bronchopneumonia, are assessing whether the ailment is
contagious. "Nothing can be said till we have the test reports of the
patients," Chatterjee said.
Chatterjee had earlier said the summer heat could have been a cause
for the sudden deaths among children. Murshidabad has witnessed
average maximum temperature of around 40 degrees Celsius this summer.
--
